Hopefully this will clear things up:   At the beginning of the year, they raised money by selling 1/3 of the equity in the company for $500 and also raised $250 through a debt issue. Cash balance: $750 = 500 + 250 They then spent $300 to buy the first stand and $200 on inventory (this is your cost of goods sold, or COGS). Cash balance: $250 = 750 - 300 - 200 At the end of year 1, we see they sold $800 of lemonade, and paid $530 in labor costs (remember, we already bought the inventory, and depreciation is a "non-cash" charge - we're accounting for having to replace the lemonade stand every 5 years). Cash balance: $520 = 250 + 800 - 530 Finally, they paid $25 in interest, leaving them with negative EBT (earnings before tax) of $15 and therefore had a tax credit of $5 (this was sort of skipped over): Cash balance: $500 = 520 - 25 + 5  Note this matches the ending cash balance (bottom line) in the cash flow statement at 8:15. With that, we have enough to spend $300 on a second lemonade stand with money to spare.

As First Assumptions said: $300 for a Stand, $200 for a year of Inventory for 1 stand [Cogs price goes up each year].  Every year inventory per stand is already paid at the "Less: COGS" My money to reinvest comes from 1 Stand as Labor costs $530  With my $530, i can buy Another Stand and Enough inventory for the new stand (Remember that the first stand already paid its inventory at the end of the year)  From now on, lets continue with the "Income Statement: The Next Four Year" My Revenue in year 2 is $1764 Less: COGS (420) [210 per stand, 2 stands] Less: Depreciation (120)  Less: Labor (530) [Thats someone else i employed] Less: Labor (530) [That me working at first stand] ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- EBIT: $184 Less: Interest (25) Less: Taxes (65) [Assuming 35% of EBIT] ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------- Net Income: $81  If we continue reinvesting our $530 of our labor, at fifth year, we shall have enough cash to buy 3 stands and continue our growth xD.   At End of fourth year, we shall have a net income of $608 That, added to the net income of third year of $286 and the secont year $81.  Were sitting at $975 + $250 (initial cash) = $1225 That means: More then enough to sustein our growth (For now xD)

My comments to the YouTube Video: "SPENT: Looking For Change" My Classification: Finances - Financial Overhaul  Rather than discussing the obvious, the results of bad decisions regarding how one spend's or does not save money, I would encourage a dialogue that looks at the "root cause" of financial woes, both for individuals and corporations. We also must not forget the fact that 'corporation's' are groups of 'individuals'!Â   There is a money management system in place, and has been since the beginning of time, that if followed correctly benefits everyone. Â It's simply: "1 + 1 = 2", "2 - 1 = 1", "0 + 0 = 0". Problem is this simple money management system does not work when emotionalism takes a front seat.  All human beings need to feel secure within themselves. How that security looks to each one is different as habits are formed early on in a person's life; before grade school! If a person has learned to make decisions using emotions as their 'yardstick', the outcome's can be disastrous. Â   Some of the causes of emotional spending are triggered by fear; the fear of being lonely, being unloved, not being able to live as one has become accustomed, no longer able to satisfy selfish desires, no longer accepted by those who are privileged. Fear turn's simple task's into monstrous nightmare's.  My opinion is that most of our governing laws have been created and put into action based on "individual's" emotion's. You must have an emotional experience that moves you to action. Something must be triggered deep within your soul which prompts you to 'do something'. When making critical decisions regarding finances, ask yourself this question, "How will this decision affect me as well as those around me"? [affect - "produce a change"Â  effect - "result" / ability to bring about a result. ] Â If at any point and time you find yourself unable to stop and ask this question before you act, then there's a good possiblity the outcome will not be the most desirable.  I also believe there is always hope! Just because your circumstances seem bleak to impossible right now, remember a journey begins with the first step. Stop where you are and begin anew. Look back only to understand those things that got you where you are today; and be honest. Start a new journey by doing things differently. The live part ends at 1:12, though, then the pre-recording kicks in. The sound technician was supposed to shut down the mic when the recording started, but the mic was still open. He figured his mistake when the recorded vocal kicked in and pulled back the mic fader on the mixer, because the mic picked up her singing in a different pitch and possibly some sound bits from the stage speakers (at 1:21). You can actually hear the quick fade-out. Also, they put a somewhat heavy reverb effect on the mic line for the live part, whereas the vocal effects on the recording are rather light. Her voice sounded rather soft in the live part (or the live mic she used was less sensitive), but her vocal on the pre-recording was pretty loud/powerful. She's a really good singer, but this wasn't a 100% live performance.

Most of Taiwanese feel some culture connection with a combination of Japan, China and US (that is, besides the aboriginal connection).    Taiwan was part of Japan for 50 years. Old Taiwanese appreciate Japanese governance way more than the suppression (including a massacre that killed tens of thousands and following state terrors aimed to eliminate Taiwanese elites) brought by Chiang Kai-Shek.  It was until president Lee Teng Hui ascending to the power that Taiwanese can freely express we are not Chinese without fear of prison or death. I have visited Japan twice now, once last summer 2016 and just now Dec. 2017.  Yes, there are definitely things that are expensive especially in Tokyo but boy, you also have lots of cheap options.  This video is really good but I just want to clarify some things and/or add info.  The Tokyo subway is vast and is operated by multiple different lines (private and government).  One is a private company which is Japan Rail who also operate the Shinkansen.  You can only get the Japan Rail pass outside of Japan as a tourist and is definitely worth it.  Like the video says, it only takes one long ride on the Shinkansen to make the 1 week pass worth it and on top of that you can ride the Japan Rail trains in the city for free.  BUT, here is the clarification, JR is not the metro/subway, it is only a portion of it.  There is a massive network of trains.  If you ONLY got the JR pass, you cannot ride the rest of the subway system in Tokyo.  You can only ride on the trains operated by JR.  Now the video is wrong in that it says you have to stand around buying tickets if you don't get the JR pass.  That's also not true.  What you should do is to buy a PASMO or SUICA card.  These are literally train debit cards and they work across all these different train companies.  They come preloaded with amounts and you can just tap your way through all the trains and it will deduct an amount each time.  No need to go buy a ticket each time and figure out how much it costs.  When the balance runs low (and you'll see your balance every time you tap),  you can just re-charge them in the ticket machines.  I got mine from Haneda airport and when I left I just returned it at the airport and I got a 500 Yen deposit refund for the card.  Concerning the food, I would definitely pick Yoshinoya over the other ones.  I find its quality just a bit better and the prices just as good.  But I had a lunch at Nakajima in Shinjuku and it is a 1 Michelin Star restaurant.  Guess how much the lunch is:  800 Yen!  So how's that for a budget lunch at a 1 Michelin star restaurant.  It opens at 11:30am so lineup early.  I waited just short of an hour but if you get there like 11:30am your wait should be shorter.  There is also a 1 Michelin star ramen place in Tokyo (near Sengoku) and cheapest ramen is 1000 Yen, its name is Tsuta.  And there are many other top notch ramen shops whose prices are cheaper too.  I also find 7 Eleven, Lawson, Family Mart to be full of good stuff to buy but you can try their local grocery stores and they have even MORE items with the same prices.  And the food shops in the train stations are amazing and tons of selection with excellent prices.  I also agree with the video's recommendation of business hotel.  I got one last year and it slept 3 of us plenty well with a kitchen/dining table too and it was just a bit higher than the capsule hotel prices.  Happy travels in Japan!

At around 25:00, he says that there are an infinite ways of construing the world, but only a limited number of ways with which one can successfully live and interact in the world.  It hit me that the same is true with regard to food.  We can come up with an infinite number of dietary plans or ways of eating, but there truly are only a limited number of ones which will sustain human health generation after generation.  For instance, when human diets were researched almost 100 years ago, there was a wide variety, ranging from insects/nuts/fish on tropical islands to oil/fat/meat in the arctic, but all the diets still met certain narrow principles (A/D consumption from animal foods, fermenting grains/nuts/dairy, broth, salt, sea food, etc.).  No groups were vegan, for instance.  I suppose after hundreds of thousands of years, you sort of figure out what doesn't keep a population thriving long-term.    And (thinking aloud) we sort of threw it all out in the 20th century.  Progress at all costs, I guess.  Maybe there's wisdom in listening to the "democracy of the past"?  We now imagine we can eat any way, live any way, marry any way, raise children any way, and it will all work out.  Maybe it magically will, or maybe, as always, nature will select the fittest and the rest will die off, either with bad health or tribal warfare.

How pleasurable or satisfying you feel doesn't depend on peak level of dopamine. It depends upon difference in baseline level and peak level of dopamine. How you feel depends upon your previous level of Dopamine as compared to present level. Many drugs just increase both baseline level and peak level instead of increasing the difference between them. A big Dopamine release makes it more challenging to achieve higher dopamine release the next time. There should not be High level nor low level of Dpamine for long.  4.Just Increasing dopamine level will make us excited but that excitement will be for very less period of time 5. Chocolate increases Dipamine 1.5 times but it goes away in few seconds. Desire of sex or act of sex increases dopamine 2 times 6. Nicotene(smoked) increases dopamine 2.5 times above base line (Very short lived) 7. Amphetamine, Cocaine, Nicotine, Sex increases dopamine in everybody that takes them. Exercise, Hard Work and Studying increasea dopamine but it is subjective 8. After achieving something, Dopamine increases but after some time it falls down. It falls down even below the baseline. The extent it drops below the baseline is directly proportional to how high the peak was. After achieving something, if you feel preety happy, the dopamine will not fall that much but if you feel extremely happy, your dopamine will fall extremely after a day or two. (Eg:- Postpartum Depression). Anyway, we return to the baseline after some time.  9. If we continue to engage in something exciting  regularly, after sometime it will be less exciting to us. 10. Some people release dopamine at higher level after a certain activity which deplete the releasable pool of dopamine. So, after sometime, dopamine falls below base level and it leads to a low feeling. Some people do the dopamine spiking activity again and again to bring back dopamine up to experience pleasure again since they are feeling low. But as we know, they have depleted the stock of releasable dopamine. The baseline begins to lower again and again. This is called ADDICTION and Addicted people don't feel pleasure at all.  11. Addiction is the progressive narrowing of things that bring you pleasure. If I am addicted to video games. I will feel happy in only playing it. I will not feel happy in exercise, study, social activity and my life will be ruined. After a some time, my system will stop releasing dopamine even after playing video games and nothing is left for me which can increase my dopamine. This is the start of depression. Spiking dopamine again and again is the main cause of decline in The baseline level. 12. If you experience a win whether it is school, sports or relationship; be highly careful about allowing yourself to experience a huge peak of Dopamine.  13. You kind of like exercise and to do exercise you increase dopamine by drinking energy drink and listen music to do exercise then you are increasing the number of conditions required to achieve the high level of dopamine by doing exercise. Don't use stimulants everytime you study or everytime you workout or anything in which you want to enjoy the process. Taking these stimulants (Music, energy drinks, Motivational reels) before the task will reduce the level of enjoyment and undermine the ability to stay motivated. The best way is to get excitement and motivation from the task itself whether it is Study or Workout. So. ENJOY THE PROCESS only. 14. Generally, most people don't like working hard. Some people do, but most people work hard in order to achieve some end goal. End goals are terrific and rewards are terrific whether or not they are monetary social or any kind. However, because of the way that dopamine relates to our perception of time, working hard at something for sake of a reward that comes afterward, can make the hard work much more challenging and make us much less likely to lean into hard work in the future.  1:41:43 My colleague at Stanford, Carol Dweck, as many of you know, has come up with this incredible theory and principle, and actually goes beyond theory and principle called   "Growth Mindset", which is this striving to be better to be in this mindset of I'm not there yet, but striving itself is the end goal.  And that of course delivers you to tremendous performance. It's been observed over and over and over again, that people that have growth mindset, kids that have growth mindset end up performing very well because they're focused on the effort itself.  And all of us can cultivate growth mindset. The neural mechanism of cultivating growth mindset involves learning to access the rewards from effort and doing. And that's hard to do because you have to engage this prefrontal component of the mesolimbic circuit. You have to tell yourself, okay, this effort is great, this effort is pleasureful.  Even though you might actually be in a state of physical pain from the exercise, or I can recall this from college, just feeling like I wanted to get up from my desk, but forcing myself to study, forcing myself and forcing myself.   What you find over time is that you can start to associate a dopamine release.  You can evoke dopamine release from the friction and the challenge that you happen to be in. You completely eliminate the ability to generate those circuits and the rewarding process of being able to reward friction while in effort, if you are focused only on the goal that comes at the end. Because of the way that dopamine marks time.  So if you say, oh, I'm going to do this very hard thing, and I'm going to push and push and push and push for that end goal that comes later.  Not only do you enjoy the process of what you're doing less, you actually make it more painful while you're engaging in it.  You make yourself less efficient at it, because if you were able to access dopamine while in effort, dopamine has all these incredible properties of increasing the amount of energy in our body, and in our mind, our ability to focus by way of dopamines conversion into epinephrin. But also you're undermining your ability to lean back into that activity the next time.  The next time you need twice as much coffee and three times as much loud music, and four times as much energy drink and the social connection just to get out the door in order to do the run or to study. So what's more beneficial in fact can serve as a tremendous amplifier on all endeavors that you engage in. Especially hard endeavors is to A, not start layering in other sources of dopamine in order to get to the starting line, not layering in other sources of dopamine in order to be able to continue, but rather to subjectively start to attach the feeling of friction and effort to an internally generated reward system. And this is not meant to be vague, this is a system that exists in your mind, that exists in the minds of humans for hundreds of thousands of years, by which you're not just pursuing the things that are innately pleasureful, food, sex, warmth, water when you're thirsty. But the beauty of this mesolimbic reward pathway that I talked about earlier is that, it includes the forebrain. So you can tell yourself the effort part is the good part.  I know it's painful, I know this doesn't feel good, but I'm focused on this. I'm going to start to access the reward. You will find the rewards, meaning the dopamine release inside of effort if you repeat this over and over again. And what's beautiful about it is that, it starts to become reflexive for all types of effort. When we focus only on the trophy, only on the grade, only on the win as the reward, you undermine that entire process. So how do you do this? You do this in those moments of the most intense friction. You tell yourself this is very painful and because it's painful, it will evoke an increase in dopamine release later, meaning it will increase my baseline in dopamine, but you also have to tell yourself that in that moment you are doing it by choice and you're doing it because you love it. And I know that sounds like lying to yourself, and in some ways it is lying to yourself, but it's lying to yourself in the context of a truth which is that you want it to feel better. You want it to feel even pleasureful. Now, this is very far and away different from thinking about the reward that comes at the end, the hot fudge sundae for after you cross the finish line and you can replace hot fudge sundae with whatever reward happens to be appealing to you. Especially when there is a great resistance to the activity, tell yourself that despite the activity being hard and difficult you are doing it BECAUSE you enjoy it! - â€œDonâ€™t spike dopamine prior to engaging in effort, and donâ€™t spike dopamine after engaging in effort. Learn to spike dopamine from effort itself.â€ - Andrew Huberman  1:47:31 - Working only for the sake of a reward that will come afterwards can make it more challenging and us less likely to do it in the future because of the way dopamine affects time perception and only being released at the reward. This relates to growth mindset, pleasure from the process, from conquering the effort (deliberate effort exposure).

In that game show, there are women/models who help introduce items contestants can win if they can guess how much each item costs.  So what the angry brother is saying, is that the model on Price Is Right isn't doing a good job presenting those items because contestants think they are worth less than they really are. An example would be if your friend bought a brand new car, and you respond "It's not smart to be brand new cars because they only go down in value the moment you drive it off the lot. I feel your 'acceptable' interpretations of the theme aren't being nearly flexible enough. People thought more outside the box and cleverly about their looks this year, and I think that's appropriate considering what happened in 2020 and is still very much happening. America is something to be critiqued, and I think a lot of the gowns did that in subtle, cheeky ways. Interpreting it just as "must be referencing an American designer or including a flag" is so limiting and not really the intention, at least not as I perceived it.   Take the look at 23:50. That is obviously another reference to Audrey Hepburn. I think it's actually super clever for a European designer to reference a European who made her fame in Hollywood, practically defined everything that came after, and eventually became an American fashion icon all without ever actually being American. Same goes for the one you named as being a ref to her at 39:14.   The "Peg the Patriarchy" look is TOTALLY on theme. Patriarchy is steeped into the very bones of the United States, and the top looks like a bulletproof vest or some kind of military gear. Having that statement on that piece and then having the tailored white pant just makes me think of going to war with the patriarchy and not caring who you have to F*ck to do it. that's a statement on America if I've ever heard one.   Grimes' sword was forged from a melted down gun and she looks like she's dressed for war- referencing the American inner conflict over the 2nd amendment. It's no coincidence her other hand is holding a book- the most vocal opponents of firearms are people who are highly educated and those who work in schools.   Lil Nas X went with looking at American excess- gold on gold on gold, lavish, taking something and making it so over-the-top that it's unbelievable. The final look was a very rock 'n roll style to me, just updated to be more sexy and less campy. I was a little shocked you called it out while literally having it facing, because it SCREAMS rock'n'roll to me. Elvis would have totally worn that... well, when he was more trim, anyway.   Olivia's look said Madonna meets punk rock to me, which suits both her musical trajectory and inspiration and fits the theme.   Some of the ones you praise highly were just so on-the-nose. Like, I feel like any third grader would come up with making a ballgown like the stripes on the flag. Having them be unwound and unfinished was a neat idea, but the overall concept was so boring. Anything that just said "Hey how can we use stars and stripes to make it American-y" missed an opportunity to do literally anything more interesting.

What he says at 15:12 is KEY for anyone wanting to draw or paint more loosely and fluidly. He basically says that he used to draw very tightly and meticulously. Repetition of this technique is what led to an intuitive understanding of form until he no longer needed to have an iron grip on what he was drawing. The understanding was inside him so he could draw the lines as quickly and fluidly as he felt like and it would still turn out looking correct. If you feel like you draw too â€œtightâ€ just keep practicing over and over and really try to internalize the form, without thinking too much about the tightness or looseness. Before you can draw loosely you draw tightly, even a savant like Kim Jung Gi.

"It's just a prank!" is a lot different from, "I'm sooo sorry, I meant that as a prank." The first means "You're a pathetic loser," and is said by bullies, and the second means, "I totally misread the situation," and invites a response. LOL, I was born and raised in midwest Brazil. Still live here. This place is usually warm and it never snows. The lowest temperature we've ever experienced here was 8 celsius, in the past.  but over the years we were used to expect for a well balanced weather between middle October and the following April. Also, during this period of the year it is normal to be raining. But year after year the average temperature is rising. And in 2018, particularly, we're almost at christmas and the weather is way far hotter than the normal (Today: 29 celsius in the evening / 19:30 pm). The UV rate today is at 15, considered at extreme level. The water volume of many rivers is decreasing year after year, and people has suffering with lack of pipered water in many days of the year. Sun power is like 200% of the normal and it's been hard to live here without using an air conditioner or sunscreen many hours a day. No, the world isn't getting warmer, definitely. We should just rake the floor of the forest.

This abuse story really hits close to home for me. I dealt with a lot of verbal and psychological (occasionally physical) abuse from my mother and her parents when I had to live at their house after my parents got divorced. My experience was very similar, with the exception that none of it was being filmed for money.   At the time I thought it was totally normal. It was hard to focus on the bad things when I was constantly showered with toys and all other kinds of gifts that I hadn't even asked for (later on I would be screamed at for being a spoiled brat because of all the things I was given). I was about 13 when this started, and I got out of it when I was 15 once my mother was convinced to leave their house while my grandfather was out of state on a business trip. I remember my grandmother yelling curses at us from the top of the stairs as we packed our most important belongings with help from my aunt.   I had a therapist legally forced on me at the time of my parents' divorce whom I honestly disliked from the moment I met her. Talking to her felt very unnatural and uncomfortable. I didn't and still don't think I needed therapy at that time, nor do I think I need it now. I'm the type of person to deal with these sorts of issues on my own with my own reasoning skills. As the sessions went on, I only had less and less to talk about. By the time I was nearing the end of my sessions, I would simply walk into her office and say "I have nothing to talk about." while the next 30 minutes was spent sitting in silence. The abuse at home I did talk about at first, but I know the way I talked about it was pretty nonchalant and tended to downplay the actual situation. At the time I was overwhelmed by all the legal intervention as at this point, I was only allowed to see my father once a week which was pretty devastating for me since I'd always had a very strong, close relationship with him. I new that if I spoke completely candidly about what was going on, I could be removed from my mother's custody which sounds good on the surface considering the abuse; however, it would have ultimately made the situation worse as my father had no chance at getting custody either because he'd had drug problems in the past, though he'd never been violent or in any way a danger to anyone.  My initial feeling about my therapist proved to be warranted as I later found out that she had been feeding any and all information I gave her to my grandfather who was the major instigator of the abuse (he is also suspected of being a pedophile and had apparently asked my mother for sexual favors while we were both living there. I also want to note that he was my mother's stepfather and not biologically related).   At this stage, maybe a month or 2 before we eventually left, I was really getting scared and desperate, so after I went out to the backyard, I called some of my friends from school and asked them for advice. They were also around the same age as me, so they weren't exactly the biggest help, though they did provide moral support and gave me the push I needed to do what I did next. I had an idea of what I wanted to do, but I lastly called my father to confirm that what I was about to do was a good idea. I then began walking quickly to a nearby park and recreational center because I didn't want my abusers around to control the situation.   When I got to the park it was about 10:00 at night. I took out my phone and called 911 and informed them of my location and that I was afraid of the members of my household. The operator informed me that they'd sent a car out and hung up, but I was still afraid of standing there by myself and was certain that my grandfather would find me soon, so I called my father's mother whom I currently live with along with my father and stepmother. She met me at the park and I ended up sitting in the car with her while we waited for the police. She had already known about the whole situation and was also very afraid for me. By the time the police showed up I was shaking and it seemed everything I needed to recount to the officer had totally left my brain. I did my best to ramble out everything that I could think of in between sobs as I'd started to cry halfway through my statement out of fear and general anxiety about what was going on. My good grandmother did best to fill in the gaps and provide information where she could.   The officer was a younger man who seemed very understanding and sympathetic. A few minutes later, another police car showed up (I later found out that the second officer was called in response to my grandfather having noticed my absence). The second officer was a woman who seemed a bit older than the other guy and was apparently his superior. I did my best to tell her the same things I told the male officer, but it was obvious that she didn't believe me, nor did she seem to care about my very real and immediate fear. I think the male officer tried to explain it to her, but she wasn't having any of it for whatever reason, and decided that I had just run away from home for shits and giggles. She wasted no time in putting me into the back of her police car and driving me back to my abusers.  When we got there, she spoke to my grandfather and laid out all the possible charges that could be pressed against me. He convinced my mother to go along with it, and I felt utterly defeated and totally helpless. After the stunt I pulled, the abuse was no longer sugarcoated with excuses and gifts but was instead openly hostile and malicious. I was lucky that it didn't last much longer.   After my mother and I had moved to a safe place, we had the legal charges against me dropped, and everything was much more peaceful. At that time, my time with my father was still limited, but with my abusive grandparents out of the picture, it was pretty easy to sneak extra time with him under my mother's nose by having him pick me up at the school bus stop before the bus came and skip that school day to spend the day with him. By the time I turned 16, there was really no way for her to keep me with her, so I packed my things and told her I was going to live with my dad. Everything has been okay since then. I still deal with a lot of anxiety and some minor OCD and have trouble getting out of the house to do things, but my psychological trauma has been kept to a minimum, which makes me feel very lucky.  Thank you for reading my story if you actually got this far. I don't often talk about it, but seeing this story play out has brought my own experience to the surface. I felt the need to document this here because I have a huge amount of empathy for these kids, especially Cody. He reminds me of myself a lot, though he's certainly dealing with this horrific abuse at a younger age than I did. I really hope he comes out of this situation relatively unscathed and grows up to become a kind, compassionate adult in the future because of it.

@ KyrstinÂ Â  Stoneking you can't fathom spending $5k on a ticket, because you travel for leisure and not business. If you're flying for business, where 100's of thousands or millions of dollars are at stake, $5k is nothing. If an exec is going to Europe, you figure not ONLY his flight time, but door to door travel. The exec travels to the airport. Gets to the airport 1-1/2 - 2 hours before departure, for check in and boarding. Flight time depends on where flying to and from, let's say 8 hours. Then there is deplaning, getting baggage, getting through customs, getting your ride, then travel to the airport. An 8 hour flight is now 12 hours or more door to door, home/office to hotel. Let's change the scenario a little. The exec does an in/out blast. He/she works at the office all/most of the day, let's say Monday. Drives to the airport and catches a 6pm flight from Chicago. That flight arrives at 8:30 am Tuesday, in London. The exec showers, dresses in fresh clothes and is off to the client/branch office, for an 11 am meeting. The exec does their business and leaves the office at 5 or 6 pm. Maybe they do a business dinner and finally checks in to their hotel at 8 or 9 pm. They get up at 6amÂ in the morning for an 11am flight. TheyÂ  have breakfast, catch a 1 hour ride to the airport, arrive 2 hours before, check in and finally board. Their flight arrives at 2 pm and get home at 4-5 pm Wednesday. That $5k seat is cheap, to make sure the exec is fresh for the meeting and relatively comfortable for the trip home. The exec left their home at 6 or 7 am Monday morning and it's now Wednesday night. Now do that everyÂ 1-2-3 months.

It is entirely a demand issue.  While an airline would like to sell only its highest revenue per square foot seats, there aren't enough customers who will pay for it.  It also turns out that schedules are also a big draw, especially for business customers, so an airline can attract more customers by having two mixed planes at 7:00am and 7:00pm than just at one of those times with all business class.  While they could probably fill one plane with all business class, in the long run, they would lose customers because of inconvenient scheduling and few options.  Essentially, economy class enables airlines to fly more planes at more times.

TheÂ Jallianwala Bagh massacre, also known as theÂ Amritsar massacre, took place on 13 April 1919 when troops of theÂ British Indian ArmyÂ under the command of ColonelÂ Reginald DyerÂ fired rifles into a crowd of Indians, who had gathered inÂ Jallianwala Bagh,Â Amritsar,Â Punjab. The civilians had assembled to condemn the arrest and deportation of two national leaders, Satya Pal andÂ Saifuddin Kitchlew. There has been much debate over whether the crowd knew of the proclamation Dyer had made banning meetings, in its supposed inefficacy, however, Raja Ram has argued that the crowd formed in deliberate defiance, being the beginning ofÂ Indian nationalism.[2]  The Jallianwalla Bagh is a public garden of 6Â to 7 acres (28,000Â m2), walled on all sides, with five entrances.[3]Â To enter, troops first blocked the entry by a tank and locked the exit. On Dyer's orders, his troops fired on the crowd for ten minutes, directing their bullets largely towards the few open gates through which people were trying to flee. OfficialÂ British IndianÂ sources gave a figure of 379 identified dead,[4]Â with approximately 1,100 wounded. The casualty number estimated by theÂ Indian National CongressÂ was more than 1,500 injured, with approximately 1,000 dead.[5]Â This "brutality stunned the entire nation",[6]Â resulting in a "wrenching loss of faith" of the general public in the intentions of the UK.[7]Â The ineffective inquiry and the initial accolades for Dyer by the House of Lords fuelled widespread anger, leading to theÂ Non-cooperation MovementÂ of 1920â€“22.[8]  On Sunday, 13Â April 1919, Dyer was convinced of a major insurrection and he banned all meetings; however this notice was not widely disseminated. That was the day of Baisakhi, the mainÂ SikhÂ festival, and many villagers had gathered in theÂ Bagh. On hearing that a meeting had assembled at Jallianwala Bagh, Dyer went with Sikh, Gurkha, Baluchi, Rajput troops from 2-9th Gurkhas, the 54th Sikhs and the 59th Sind Rifles[9]Â to a raised bank and ordered them to shoot at the crowd. Dyer continued the firing for about ten minutes, until the ammunition supply was almost exhausted. Dyer stated that 1,650 rounds had been fired, a number apparently derived by counting empty cartridge cases picked up by the troops.[10]  Dyer was initially lauded by conservative forces in the empire, but in July 1920 he was censured and forced to retire by the House of Commons.[11]Â He became a celebrated hero in the UK among most of the people connected to theÂ British Raj,[12]Â for example, theÂ House of Lords,[13]Â but unpopular in theÂ House of Commons, which voted against Dyer as a Colonel. He was disciplined by being removed from his appointment, was passed over for promotion and was prohibited from further employment in India.[14][15]Â Upon his deathÂ Rudyard KiplingÂ declared that Dyer 'did his duty as he saw it'.[16]Â The massacre some historians have argued caused a re-evaluation of the army's role, in which the new policy becameÂ minimum force, however, later British actions during the Mau Mau insurgencies have led Huw Bennett to question this school of thought.[17]Â The army was retrained and developed less violent tactics for crowd control.[18]Â Some historians consider the episode a decisive step towards the end of British rule in India.[19] At 9:00 on the morning of 13 April, the traditional festival ofÂ Baisakhi, Colonel Reginald Dyer, the acting military commander for Amritsar and its environs, proceeded through the city with several city officials, announcing the implementation of a pass system to enter or leave Amritsar, a curfew beginning at 20:00 that night and a ban on all processions and public meetings of four or more persons. The proclamation was read and explained in English, Urdu, Hindi and Punjabi, but few paid it any heed or appear to have learned of it later.[40]Â Meanwhile, the local CID had received intelligence of the planned meeting in the Jallianwala Bagh through word of mouth and plainclothes detectives in the crowds. At 12:40, Dyer was informed of the meeting and returned to his base at around 13:30 to decide how to handle it.[41]  By mid-afternoon, thousands of Sikhs, Muslims and Hindus had gathered in theÂ Jallianwala BaghÂ (garden) near theÂ Harmandir SahibÂ in Amritsar. Many who were present had earlier worshipped at the Golden Temple, and were passing through the Bagh on their way home. The Bagh was (and is) an open area of six to seven acres, roughly 200 yards by 200 yards in size, and surrounded by walls roughly 10 feet in height. Balconies of houses three to four stories tall overlooked the Bagh, and five narrow entrances opened onto it, several with locked gates. During the rainy season, it was planted with crops, but served as a local meeting-area and playground for much of the year.[42]Â In the center of the Bagh was aÂ samadhiÂ (cremation site) and a large well partly filled with water which measured about 20 feet in diameter.[42]  Apart from pilgrims, Amritsar had filled up over the preceding days with farmers, traders and merchants attending the annual Baisakhi horse and cattle fair. The city police closed the fair at 14:00 that afternoon, resulting in a large number of people drifting into the Jallianwala Bagh. It was estimated that about 20,000 to 25,000 people had gathered in the Bagh by the time of the meeting. Dyer sent an aeroplane to overfly the Bagh and estimate the size of the crowd.[42]Â By this time, both Colonel Dyer and Deputy Commissioner Irving, the senior civil authority for Amritsar, were well aware of the meeting, but took no actions to prevent it or send police to peacefully disperse the crowds. This would later be a serious criticism levelled at both Dyer and Irving.  An hour after the meeting began as scheduled at 16:30, Colonel Dyer arrived at the Bagh with a group of ninety Sikh, Gurkha, Baluchi (note that the Baluch Regiment of the British Indian Army did not have Baluch troops, the British having failed in their efforts to get the Baluch to enlist and serve; the Baluch continued to fight an insurgency of varying intensity with the British from 1839 to 1947. The Baluch regiment was staffed by troops from the Punjab and other areas of India), Rajput from 2-9th Gurkhas, the 54th Sikhs and the 59th Sind Rifles soldiers.[9]Â Fifty of them were armed withÂ .303Â Leeâ€“EnfieldÂ bolt-action rifles. It is not clear whether Dyer had specifically chosen troops from that ethnic group due to their proven loyalty to the British or that they were simply the Sikh and non-Sikh units most readily available. He had also brought two armored cars armed with machine guns; however, the vehicles were left outside, as they were unable to enter the Bagh through the narrow entrances. The Jallianwala Bagh was surrounded on all sides by houses and buildings and had few narrow entrances. Most of them were kept permanently locked. The main entrance was relatively wide, but was guarded heavily by the troops backed by the armoured vehicles.  Dyerâ€”without warning the crowd to disperseâ€”blocked the main exits. He 'explained' later that this act "was not to disperse the meeting but to punish the Indians for disobedience."[43]Dyer ordered his troops to begin shooting toward the densest sections of the crowd. Firing continued for approximately ten minutes. Cease-fire was ordered only when ammunition supplies were almost exhausted, after approximately 1,650 rounds were spent.[10]  Many people died in stampedes at the narrow gates or by jumping into the solitary well on the compound to escape the shooting. A plaque, placed at the site after independence states that 120 bodies were removed from the well. The wounded could not be moved from where they had fallen, as a curfew was declared, and many more died during the night.[44].

WARNING FOR PIZZA NOVICES: Having followed the recipe, I would say that this 12:45 video makes it look deceptively simple to get a perfect pie on the first try. I'm not saying it can't be done -I'm  just saying a lot of things can go wrong. Stupid things like not having correct size containers for the dough to rise, or the pizza sticking to the peel. Also, I did not pay enough attention to his note that you will probably need to add a lot more flour than 5 cups to knead the dough to the correct consistancy. My advice is to watch lots of videos on making NY-style pizza before you give it a go, and set your expectations low for your first few pies, so you won't be too disappointed if it does not turn out perfect when you start out. Good luck!

The diagram at 1:18 makes no sense at all because if the air on the right side is not able to resist the ball's spin enough to cause it to spin the other way, then the ball shouldnâ€™t move to the left. The only way the ball should move to the left is 1. if the ball was spinning the other way or 2. if the air on the left travels all the way around the ball parallel with its spin, but that's not what the diagram shows. You see what I mean? EDIT: Oh wait I get it now, I guess the ball has little resistance against the air so that allows it to easily spin along the air on the right and the left air blowing over it pushes it away from the right air, so that makes sense, yeah. It's just that if the ball's spin was fully resisted by the air, then the diagram would make no sense. And even then, the diagram could still be wrong if the air had enough resistance on the ball's spin to overpower the amount of spin you applied to it and thus not allow it to spin.

The statement at 1:15, being "The ball pushes air one way, so the air applies an equal force on the ball the other way" describes third-law pairs, which alone do not result in any net force. This description is wrong, or at least incomplete. The air on the left, being shear-dragged by the surface of the ball, is moving faster, creating a low pressure zone while the air on the right side is slower, creating a higher pressure zone. The unequal pressures on either side of the ball result in the net force which pushed the ball.

At 2:39:00 in this video, Dr. Huberman says when we want to/have the will to do something but we keep CHOOSING (subconsciously & consciously) to let ourselves be distracted from doing it; 'til we don't do it at all, resulting in feeling disappointed in ourselves, THEN there are 2 ways of looking at it:       1) We can focus on our thinking & SEE how our inner thoughts/dialogue are serving to help us NOT DO the thing (by thinking ; it's too hard, it'll hurt, I'm not smart enough etc.) OR how our thinking can/COULD BE used to serve us to GET US TO DO IT (by thinking ; I'll feel so good when I've DONE it, I'll feel proud of myself/ happy I DID overcome what I HAD TO to accomplish MY goal, by the strength of MY WILL, the outcome'll be YAY!! {= how we envision that outcome will benefit us/make us feel empowered about ourselves + STOP making us feel like/think we're lazy, useless or UNable etc. each time we don't do what we WANT to do.} OR we can;      #2) Decide to ACCEPT OURSELVES & our choice to NOT DO what we keep avoiding doing. We CAN CHOOSE to NOT DO IT, if we DON"T REALLY WANT the outcome envisioned or WE DECIDE there's not enough payoff for us to DO it.        Like I"ve told my kids, if they want a mate but they'd RATHER stay online, sleep, read THAN DO ANY & everything they could be doing that WOULD help them connect with people & actualy find a mate; THEN maybe they needed to STOP condemning themselves & STOP feeling less than others for not having a mate yet. Maybe they needed to ALLOW themselves the choice, GIVE themselves the ok to not be seeking a mate for the time being & STOP letting other's expectations make them feel like they should be SEEKING A MATE or already HAVE one. AXXEPT THEMSELVES and still be proud of themselves. A novel idea to many.       I think it's the CRUX of WHY people feel unhappy, when we will spend so much time downing ourselves for who we are, based on something we've been taught tobelieve/ think that was mplanted in our heads by society, media & SOME people's opinions that our brain uses to keep telling us that "WE'RE NOT GOOD ENOUGHas we ARE, not "as good as" others.       So if you like just how you are, you CAN accept yourself & stop beating yourself up, it's YOUR LIFE.        But if you really DO WANT something you CAN also OWN THAT & reframe your thoughts related to it to more  empower you to ASSIST YOU to get it done.         I found acceptance in some areas AND changing negative thoughts in others; to be how I stopped judging myself & beating myself up all the time. We can BE GOOD TO OURSELVES, LOVE & ACCEPT ourselves, AND focus in on things that really do matter to us.

Russian and Moroccan Jews have completely different traditions and values. Russian Jews tend to be far more conservative then Moroccan Jews.   For example, in Judaism, there is something called a Mitzva. While this word does not translate well into English, you can think of it like a religious Event. It could be a good thing like a wedding, or a bad thing like a funeral. Now both Russian and Moroccan Jews have very different ways of observing Mitzvas. Russian Jews tend to focus more on the praying aspect of Mitzvas and have celebration as a secondary thing if at all. Moroccan Jews however, do the exact opposite. They will focus almost entirely on celebration often even during bad Mitzvas. The mindset here is that you should be celebrating being alive and even during a funeral the person who died wouldn't want you to be depressed.   This mindset tends to make a lot of Sephardic Jews seem weird to other Jews. I remember when my grandparents (Ashkenazi ones) came back from an organized holocaust tour (they were visiting a bunch of the concentration camps), they told me about a running joke that the Sephardic buses were were the party buses of the trip. This is because Sephardic Jews tend to prefer celebrating being alive than mourning the dead.

Alexyum S.  Judging by 0:42, the wheels rotate about as much as the handle bars - just in the opposite direction, so I don't think it's a sensitivity issue.  I think the reason that people wobble so much when they start isn't a sensitivity thing.  It's just that when you start on a bike, you have to make a ton of micro adjustments to get your balance.  Most of those adjustments are small, unconscious, and quick, so someone trained in making adjustments on a normal bike will create twice the rotational instability, which will create a larger unbalance issue.  You really need to be in complete control to get it on your first try, otherwise only several weeks of training will suffice.
